  <h1>How to Count Calories: A Beginner's Guide</h1>
  <div class="meta">Last updated: July 2026 &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; 6 min read</div>
  <div class="article-meta">Reviewed by <strong>Sarah Mitchell, BSc Nutrition</strong> &nbsp;·&nbsp; Updated June 2026 &nbsp;·&nbsp; 8 min read</div>

  <div class="article-section">
    <p>Calorie counting has the strongest evidence base of any weight management strategy. A large 2019 meta-analysis found that self-monitoring of food intake is one of the most consistent predictors of successful weight loss. But it only works when done accurately — and most beginners make the same mistakes that undermine their results.</p>
    <div class="highlight-box"><strong>The evidence:</strong> Studies show people who track food intake lose 2–3× more weight than those who don't, even when given identical dietary advice. The act of tracking increases awareness and accountability — two of the most powerful behavioural weight loss tools.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="article-section">
    <h2>What You'll Need</h2>
    <h3>A food scale (essential)</h3>
    <p>The single most important tool for accurate calorie counting. Cup and tablespoon measurements are notoriously inaccurate — studies show people underestimate portion sizes by 20–50% using visual estimation. A digital kitchen scale costing $10–20 eliminates this error entirely.</p>
    <h3>A tracking app</h3>
    <p>Apps like MyFitnessPal, Cronometer, or Lose It have extensive food databases that make logging fast. Cronometer is particularly useful for micronutrient tracking alongside calories. Most are free for basic calorie tracking.</p>
    <h3>Your calorie target</h3>
    <p>Use our <a href="calorie-calculator.html" style="color:var(--accent);">Calorie Calculator</a> to find your TDEE, then subtract 400–500 kcal to set your daily target.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="article-section">
    
<div class="card" style="padding:20px;margin:20px 0;overflow-x:auto;">
  <p style="font-size:.75rem;font-weight:600;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.08em;color:var(--ink3);margin-bottom:14px;">Accuracy of common calorie estimation methods</p>
