<h2>How to Track Accurately</h2>
    <h3>1. Weigh everything — including liquids</h3>
    <p>Oil, butter, sauces, and drinks are the most commonly underestimated calorie sources. One tablespoon of olive oil is 120 kcal; a "splash" of cream in coffee can easily be 50–80 kcal. Weigh oils and sauces on a scale, and track all drinks except plain water.</p>
    <h3>2. Log before you eat, not after</h3>
    <p>Pre-logging meals allows you to adjust portions before eating. Post-logging is less accurate because portion sizes are harder to recall precisely and there's less motivation to be honest about oversized servings.</p>
    <h3>3. Use food database entries carefully</h3>
    <p>Many food database entries are user-submitted and inaccurate. For packaged foods, scan the barcode or use the nutritional information on the label. For whole foods, use USDA or government database entries, which are verified.</p>
    <h3>4. Account for cooking methods</h3>
    <p>Chicken breast raw and cooked have different weights but the same calorie content. Log meat as raw weight (before cooking) for consistency, or use "cooked" entries when weighing after cooking. Mixing these introduces significant error.</p>
    <h3>5. Tracking hawker and mixed rice stall meals</h3>
    <p>Meals from hawker stalls and nasi campur (mixed rice) counters are genuinely harder to track precisely, since portion sizes, oil quantity, and gravy amounts vary stall to stall. A practical approach: estimate conservatively (round up rather than down for oil-heavy dishes like fried noodles or curries), weigh a similar home-cooked version once to calibrate your estimate, and prioritise weighing the things you can control — your rice portion, for example — even if the side dishes are estimated.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="article-section">
    <h2>Common Mistakes That Undermine Tracking</h2>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Mistake</th><th>Typical Error</th><th>Fix</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Eyeballing portions</td><td>+200–400 kcal/day</td><td>Use a food scale always</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Not tracking cooking oils</td><td>+100–200 kcal/day</td><td>Weigh oil before adding to pan</td></tr>
