  <div class="article-section">
    <h2>Making Tracking Sustainable</h2>
    <p>Tracking doesn't need to be permanent. Most people track carefully for 4–8 weeks, calibrating their intuition about portion sizes and calorie content, then shift to a looser approach (tracking main meals, estimating others) that they can maintain indefinitely.</p>
    <p>Research supports this: even imperfect tracking produces significantly better outcomes than no tracking. A 3-day food diary every month or so can recalibrate portion awareness as habits drift over time.</p>
  </div>


  <div class="article-section">
    <h2>How Accurate Is Calorie Counting? Common Sources of Error</h2>
    <p>Even careful calorie counters underestimate intake by an average of 20–30%, according to multiple studies using doubly labelled water (the gold standard for measuring actual calorie burn). The main sources of error:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Food database inaccuracies:</strong> Restaurant meals can vary by ±20% from listed calories. Home-cooked meals depend on weighing ingredients. Generic entries (e.g. "pasta, cooked") can be 15–25% off due to moisture content variation.</li>
      <li><strong>Portion size estimation:</strong> Studies consistently show people underestimate portion sizes visually. Using a kitchen scale for the first 2–4 weeks establishes accurate reference points that improve long-term estimation.</li>
      <li><strong>Cooking oils and condiments:</strong> A tablespoon of olive oil is 120 kcal. A "drizzle" poured by most people is 2–3 tablespoons. Oils, dressings, and sauces are the most commonly underlogged calorie sources.</li>
      <li><strong>Liquid calories:</strong> Drinks are frequently omitted from logs. A standard latte (whole milk) is 180 kcal; a smoothie can be 400–800 kcal depending on ingredients.</li>
      <li><strong>Calorie absorption varies:</strong> Raw vs cooked food, food processing level, and individual gut microbiome differences all affect how many calories are actually absorbed from what you eat — independent of what the label says.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="callout"><p>💡 The goal of calorie counting isn't perfect accuracy — it's calibrated awareness. Even rough tracking reduces intake by an average of 200–300 kcal/day compared to no tracking, simply by increasing mindfulness.</p></div>
  </div>

  <div class="article-section">
    <h2>Best Apps for Calorie Counting in 2026</h2>
    <p>The right app depends on how much detail you want and whether you're cooking at home or eating out frequently:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>MyFitnessPal:</strong> Largest food database (~18 million entries), good barcode scanner, connects to fitness trackers. Free version adequate for most users; Premium adds macro goal features.</li>
      <li><strong>Cronometer:</strong> More accurate micronutrient data (vitamins, minerals) — best choice if nutrition quality matters beyond just calories and macros. Slightly smaller database than MFP.</li>
      <li><strong>Lose It!:</strong> Clean interface, strong meal planning features, AI-based photo food recognition for quick logging without searching the database.</li>
      <li><strong>Nutracheck (UK-focused):</strong> Better database for UK and European food products including major supermarket items; useful if you frequently eat UK-branded foods.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>All apps are only as accurate as the entries you use. Always cross-check new entries against the nutrition label on the physical product — user-submitted entries in large databases frequently contain errors.</p>
  </div>

