  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How long do I need to count calories?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">Research shows that consistent tracking for 3–4 months builds a lasting understanding of the calorie content of commonly eaten foods, which many people then apply intuitively without strict tracking. A common approach is to track carefully during an initial period, then periodically recheck when progress stalls or after habit changes.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Are calorie counting apps accurate?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">App databases are generally accurate for packaged foods with barcodes. User-entered data for restaurant meals and homemade recipes is less reliable. Apps are tools for estimation, not precise measurement — a ±100–200 kcal/day inaccuracy is typical and acceptable for weight management purposes.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can calorie counting become obsessive or harmful?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">For most people, calorie tracking is a practical tool that improves awareness without causing harm. However, for individuals with a history of disordered eating, obsessive tracking behaviour, or significant food anxiety, calorie counting can be counterproductive. Alternative approaches (portion control, food quality focus, structured meal plans) are equally valid.</div>
  </div>
